@John Caccioppo Yeah, I'm having all kinds of personal revelations through J and A's relationship. The more I learn about personality disorders, the patterns in all relationships where a person has an avoidant or dependent personality and the other has a cluster b disorder are so similar it's creepy. When the person I was with had a psychotic episode, it seemed absolutely supernatural, I was in shock for months after it happened and I've been reading about it ever since. It has profoundly affected me and the way I look at the world. The main problem for me is that I could see a very good, scared person in her, but it was stuffed way down inside. Like you said, Johnny is a fixer, for me it's because of intense compassion (too intense), but I swear there is a good person trapped by some kind of dark force, and it seems like I'm supposed to figure it out. Some people might label that as "cognitive dissonance" I don't know, our minds are so tricky, but to me it feels supernatural, if anyone experienced what I did they would feel the same.

@Hum Bull I feel like they need to have all control taken away because they will abuse it, but I also think education and CBT might be effective.  Carefully administered, maybe even drugs.  But nothing works by itself and rarely does anyone have the resources to help a person like that.

I believe the fear of social isolation causes people to go down paths they don't understand and which are counterintuitive to others.  They might fear abandonment so much they try to enslave others, try to possess or consume them.  

I think in this case, maybe Johnny's avoidant personality may have driven Amber to become the worst possible version of herself and his guilt prevented him from taking corrective or even defensive action.

He had a reputation for trying to fix his partners, I understand.  This is a nightmarish lesson to have to learn.  It's interesting to speculate but terrible at the same time. What a trainwreck to have to live through.

It's not that easy to leave someone who abuse you. It's not like they just up and hit you one day out of the blue, they break you down first, little by little. Gaslighting and crazy making is very powerful psychological tools to break someone down with, and once someone is broken enough? Well, they can't leave that easy. What was once them isn't there anymore, you got a broken sense of self esteem, you genuinely start to believe you're the crazy one, you think you're worthless, you are emotionally completely shattered. 
When you're that confused about what's right and wrong, broken and manipulated it is very very very hard to conjure up the strength to stand up for yourself. It's very much a process going from the start of a relationship with someone you think loves and respects you, (love bombing is a early sign of a person being dangerous. But if you don't know what it is, it's easy to fall for that intense charm and attention someone gives you. Look it up) till the situation where you're abused by that very same person. They don't show you who they are until they got you under control and broken down. 

That's why Johnny Depp didn't leave until she were able to do him a lot of serious harm publicly. 
That's why anyone that falls victim to domestic abuse have a hard time leaving their abuser. "Why don't you just leave?". Honey it isn't that easy. Far far from. But I'm glad you haven't had to experience that type of hell. Do yourself a favor though, put some time into researching this subject. It can literally save your life one day.
